<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="102" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,186,212]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. MALE. Mesopleuron beneath without precoxal tubercle. S2 laterally with trace of felt line (a few punctures in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tsuneki" authorityYear="1972" box="[302,416,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Smicromyrme" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fukudai">
<emphasis box="[302,416,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">P. fukudai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, lacking in 
<taxonomicName box="[558,697,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Petersenidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hylonome">
<emphasis box="[558,697,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">P. hylonome</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). T7 with median glabrous area. Volsella without paracuspis, at most with setose tubercle between cuspis and digitus. FEMALE. Propodeum narrower than or as broad as pronotum; scutellar scale distinct; T2 disc with two laterally disposed white to golden setal spots; T2 apex without pale setal band, rarely with sparse fringe or medially interrupted band; pygidium defined by lateral carinae and usually entirely smooth. The pygidium of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lelej" authorityYear="1992" box="[552,694,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Petersenidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,694,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Petersenidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually wider and defined by stronger lateral carinae than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lelej" authorityYear="1996" box="[151,306,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Krombeinidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,306,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Krombeinidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="102" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Remarks</emphasis>
. Like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lelej" authorityYear="1996" box="[380,535,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Krombeinidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[380,535,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Krombeinidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this large genus is more reliably defined by male morphology than female. Cur- rently the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lelej" authorityYear="1992" box="[341,483,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Petersenidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[341,483,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Petersenidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes 44 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Lelej, A. S." box="[725,852,474,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" refId="ref2365" refString="Lelej, A. S. (2005) Catalogue of the Mutillidae (Hymenoptera) of the Oriental Region. Dalnauka, Vladivostok, 252 pp." type="book" year="2005">Lelej 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pagliano, G. &amp; Brothers, D. J. &amp; Cambra, R. &amp; Lelej, A. S. &amp; Lo Cascio, P. &amp; Matteini Palmerini, M. &amp; Scaramozzino, P. L. &amp; Williams, K. A. &amp; Romano, M." box="[865,1096,475,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" pagination="5 - 425" refId="ref2543" refString="Pagliano, G., Brothers, D. J., Cambra, R., Lelej, A. S., Lo Cascio, P., Matteini Palmerini, M., Scaramozzino, P. L., Williams, K. A. &amp; Romano, M. (2020) Checklist of names in Mutillidae (Hymenoptera), with illustrations of selected species. Bollettino del Museo Regionale di Scienze Naturali di Torino, 36 (1 - 2), 5 - 425." type="journal article" year="2020">
Pagliano 
<emphasis box="[971,1029,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
), which are widespread in the Oriental region and penetrate to the Eastern Palaearctic. Only 
<typeStatus box="[866,914,511,537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">type</typeStatus>
species is known in both sexes, while 22 are known in male and 
<quantity box="[372,429,547,573]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.334" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" unit="in" value="21.0">21 in</quantity>
females. There are no reviews or revision of this large genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
